AB  - The first proof of reproduction of little bustard in Provence and the Gard dates from the beginning of this century. Before then it was a rare wintering species. Increased cultivation in the Crau has allowed it to increase considerably, so that it is now common in the area. Some 423-470 singing males were estimated on the Crau. Twenty or so other centres of population occur elsewhere in Provence, accounting for 90-100 individuals. Winter counts in the Crau, the only wintering site in the study area, showed there to be maxima of 900-1300 birds, 1972-1984, one of the highest concentrations of the species in the world.-from English summary
